SIMPLE: property
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Property
<hw>Prop"er*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Properties</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>proprete</ets>,
OF. <ets>propret⟦eacute⟧</ets> property, F. <ets>propret⟦eacute⟧</ets>
neatness, cleanliness, <ets>propri⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧</ets> property, fr.
L. <ets>proprietas</ets>. See <er>Proper</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Propriety</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is proper to anything; a peculiar quality
of a thing; that which is inherent in a subject, or naturally essential
to it; an attribute; <as>as, sweetness is a <ex>property</ex> of
sugar</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Property</qex> is correctly a synonym for peculiar quality;
but it is frequently used as coextensive with quality in general.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In physical science, the properties of matter are
distinguished to the three following classes: 1. <xex>Physical
properties</xex>, or those which result from the relations of bodies to
the physical agents, light, heat, electricity, gravitation, cohesion,
adhesion, etc., and which are exhibited without a change in the
composition or kind of matter acted on. They are color, luster, opacity,
transparency, hardness, sonorousness, density, crystalline form,
solubility, capability of osmotic diffusion, vaporization, boiling,
fusion, etc. 2. <xex>Chemical properties</xex>, or those which are
conditioned by affinity and composition; thus, combustion, explosion,
and certain solutions are reactions occasioned by chemical properties.
Chemical properties are identical when there is identity of composition
and structure, and change according as the composition changes. 3.
<xex>Organoleptic properties</xex>, or those forming a class which can
not be included in either of the other two divisions. They manifest
themselves in the contact of substances with the organs of taste, touch,
and smell, or otherwise affect the living organism, as in the manner of
medicines and poisons.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An acquired or artificial quality; that which is
given by art, or bestowed by man; <as>as, the poem has the
<ex>properties</ex> which constitute excellence</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The exclusive right of possessing, enjoying, and
disposing of a thing; ownership; title.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here I disclaim all my paternal care,⟦br⟧
Propinquity and <qex>property</qex> of blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall man assume a <qex>property</qex> in man?</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1149 --></p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That to which a person has a legal title, whether in
his possession or not; thing owned; an estate, whether in lands, goods,
or money; <as>as, a man of large <ex>property</ex>, or small
<ex>property</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>All the adjuncts of a play except
the scenery and the dresses of the actors; stage requisites.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will draw a bill of <qex>properties</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Propriety; correctness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Camden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Literary property</b></col>. <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Literary</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Property man</b></col><-- or
prop man -->, <cd>one who has charge of the ⟦ldquo⟧properties⟦rdquo⟧ of
a theater.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Property</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Property
<hw>Prop"er*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To invest which properties, or qualities.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a property of; to appropriate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have here <qex>propertied</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prophane</ent>⟦br⟧
